e piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Barley. Those in Lancashire and Yorkshire are named with Old English <i>bār</i> ‘wild boar’ or <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. A place of the same name in Hertfordshire has as its first element an unattested Old English byname <i>Be(o)ra</i> (from <i>bera</i> ‘bear’).","English: metonymic occupational name for a grower or seller of barley, from Middle English <i>barli</i>, <i>barlich</i> ‘barley’ (Old English <i>bærlic</i>, originally an adjective derivative of <i>bær</i> ‘barley’, a byform of <i>bere</i>).","Americanized form of South German   Behrle   or of its Swiss German cognates <b>Beerli</b>, <b>Berli</b>, or <b>Berly</b>, and probably also of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. Compare   Berley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Behrle","meanings":["South German (Württemberg): from a pet form of   Behr   ‘bear’, including from a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with Old High German <i>bero</i> ‘bear’.","Altered form of Norwegian <b>Berle</b>: habitational name from a farmstead in the county of Sogn og Fjordane, so named with Old Norse <i>barth</i> ‘rim, edge’."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"